questions.question:
Consider two relations describing teams and players in a sports league:
  teams(tid, tname): tid, tname are team-id and team-name, respectively
  players(pid, pname, tid): pid, pname, and tid denote player-id, player-name and the team-id of the player, respectively

Which ONE of the following tuple relational calculus queries returns the name of the players who play for the team named 'MI'?

A. { p | p in players AND (exists t)(t in teams AND t.tname = 'MI' AND t.tid = p.tid) }
B. { p.pname | p in players AND (exists t)(t in teams AND t.tname = 'MI') }
C. { p.pname | p in players AND (exists t)(t in teams AND t.tname = 'MI' AND t.tid = p.tid) }
D. { p | p in players AND (exists t)(t in teams AND t.tname = 'MI' AND t.tid = p.tid) }

steps.apply:
Option B: { p.pname | p in players AND (exists t)(t in teams AND t.tname = 'MI') }
This has NO join condition t.tid = p.tid. It finds all players such that SOME team named 'MI' exists — which returns ALL players in the database, regardless of their team. This is incorrect.

Option C: { p.pname | p in players AND (exists t)(t in teams AND t.tname = 'MI' AND t.tid = p.tid) }
This correctly requires that there EXISTS a team t with tname = 'MI' AND t.tid = p.tid — meaning the player's own tid must match the 'MI' team's tid. This is the correct join.
